<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-05-24T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-05-24T03:00:00-05:00" n="100" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d100">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.11/1146: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-05-24T16:00:00+08:00">May 24, 1930—4
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received May 24—9:10 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>367. Legation’s 365, May 23, 6 p.m., paragraph 2.<note n="25" xml:id="d100fn25"><hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_13">p. 13</ref>.</note> Following telegram dated April 23 has been
                            received from the Commander in Chief, United States Asiatic Fleet:
                                <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“The American Minister has written to the Consul General at
                                    Hankow and advised him that Americans should be discouraged from
                                    going to Kuling this summer. I have discussed the question with
                                    the Minister and informed him that it would be impracticable to
                                    afford protection with naval forces.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer>For the Minister:<lb/><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Perkins</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>